    <h1>Sexism in Society</h1>
   <h4>From a very young age, girls are exposed to media and ideas that make them think that they have to look and act a certain way. Not only that, but they are also told that there are limited career options for them. Young girls are also faced with double standards: they are told to speak up for what they beleive in, but not TOO loudly. These girls then grow up surrounded by media, conversations, and more, telling them that they have to be a certain way. These ideas then stick with them through adulthood and effect many of their decisions and life choices.</h4>
    <br>
    
    <h3>Examples of Sexism in Society</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>
        Religious Sexism and Discrimination: Although people are told to beleive in whatever god they want, women are continously left out of religious events and ceremonies simply because of their gender.
      </li>
      <li>
        Double Standards: Women and girls are told to be polite, quiet, and live up to certain expectations. Men and boys, however, have very different standards. Due to these expectations, girls start to realize from a very young age that they are treated differently than boys.
      </li>
      <li>
        Media: Throughout many forms of media, women and girls are objectified while men and boys display traits of masculinity. This then leads women and girls to feel like they are not enough, and it leads society to beleive that men and boys are superior to women and girls.
      </li>
      <li>Education: Many girls all over the world are not given access to education simply because of their gender.</li>
    </ul>
